== Required PPE ==
* Nitrile gloves (latex does not provide adequate protection against photopolymer resins)
* Safety glasses or splash goggles
* Lab coat or chemical-resistant apron
* Respiratory protection if ventilation is inadequate (half-face respirator with organic vapor cartridge)

== Resin Handling ==
# Only open resin bottles in a ventilated area.
# Shake or stir resin thoroughly before pouring into the printer vat.
# Pour slowly to avoid splashing. Use a funnel if needed.
# Reseal bottles immediately after use to prevent UV exposure and contamination.
# Store resin in a cool, dark location away from windows and UV sources.
# Check resin expiration dates — expired resin may not cure properly.

== Post-Processing ==

=== Washing ===
# Remove the build platform from the printer carefully, keeping it level to avoid dripping.
# Wash prints in IPA (isopropyl alcohol, 90%+) or the manufacturer-recommended wash solution.
# Use two wash stages for best results: a dirty wash (2-3 minutes) followed by a clean wash (2-3 minutes).
# Do not exceed recommended wash times — over-washing can soften fine details.
# Allow prints to air dry completely before curing.

=== Post-Curing ===
# Place washed and dried prints in a UV curing station.
# Follow the resin manufacturer's recommended cure time and temperature.
# Rotating or flipping parts during curing ensures even exposure.
# Parts are safe to handle without gloves only after full post-cure.

== Printer Maintenance ==
* Inspect the FEP film or release membrane regularly for scratches, cloudiness, or punctures.
* Filter resin in the vat through a paint strainer before long storage periods.
* Clean the build platform with IPA between prints.
* Keep the printer's UV screen or laser optics clean and free of resin contamination.

== Storage and Shelf Life ==
* Unopened resin: follow manufacturer expiration date (typically 1-2 years).
* Opened resin: use within 6 months for best results.
* Resin left in the printer vat: use within 1-2 weeks or filter and return to the bottle.
